I found that express, when status code is `204`(no content) or `304` (not modified), is explicitly removing any previously set body (and 3 headers). See [source code](https://github.com/expressjs/express/blob/9375a9afa9d7baa814b454c7a6818a7471aaef00/lib/response.js#L192-L198).

``` js
// strip irrelevant headers
if (204 === this.statusCode || 304 === this.statusCode) {
  this.removeHeader('Content-Type');
  this.removeHeader('Content-Length');
  this.removeHeader('Transfer-Encoding');
  chunk = '';
}
```

Shouldn't express throw an error instead of trying to make magical things?

If the developper has set (or is writing) a body, thats because that's what he want to do. And if the developper is setting incompatible status/body/headers, I think that express :
1. Shouldn't alter initial developper wishes
2. Can ne nice and throw an **explicit error** to scatterbrain developper

Related:
- Here is a PR with a similar conversation on the limits of express responsibility : https://github.com/expressjs/express/pull/2011
- Headers are not removed in 204/304 when using `.end()` https://github.com/expressjs/express/pull/3076
- Auto 204 with empty body https://github.com/expressjs/express/pull/604 is ok. But not with empty json https://github.com/expressjs/express/issues/1800
- How Node.js HttpServer is dealing with "no body" statuses : [_http_server.js](https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/master/lib/_http_server.js#L201-L214)

Considering you agree, I'm aware this is a breaking change, but we can take advantage of the new 5.0 express version.

